title: Comedian Joan Rivers dead at 81
description:
Comedy pioneer Joan Rivers has died at the age of 81, according to a statement released by her daughter Melissa Rivers. 

Comedian Joan Rivers died in a New York hospital Thursday afternoon, a week after suffering cardiac arrest during a medical procedure, her daughter said.

"She passed peacefully at 1:17 p.m. surrounded by family and close friends," Melissa Rivers said in a written statement.

Rivers, 81, had been on life support at Manhattan's Mount Sinai hospital, where she was taken after she stopped breathing at the Yorkville Endoscopy clinic last Thursday.

Rivers was undergoing an apparently minor elective procedure at the clinic when she suffered cardiac and respiratory arrest, according to the New York Fire Department.

Paramedics took her by ambulance to Mount Sinai Hospital, about a mile from the clinic, where she was initially listed in critical condition.

The outpatient clinic is now being investigated by the New York State Department of Health, spokesman James O'Hara said.

Her death also has triggered an investigation by the New York medical examiner's office, its spokeswoman, Julie Bolcer, told CNN. "The cause and manner of death will be announced at some point," she said.

The Rivers family made very little information about her medical condition public, finally confirming Tuesday that she was on life support.

"My son and I would like to thank the doctors, nurses, and staff of Mount Sinai Hospital for the amazing care they provided for my mother," her daughter said. "Cooper and I have found ourselves humbled by the outpouring of love, support, and prayers we have received from around the world. They have been heard and appreciated.'

Melissa Rivers and her son Cooper have spent the past week by Rivers' hospital bedside, rushing there last Thursday when they learned of her illness.

'My mother's greatest joy in life was to make people laugh," Melissa Rivers said. "Although that is difficult to do right now, I know her final wish would be that we return to laughing soon."

The clinic has not responded to repeated calls from CNN about the state's investigation.

Yorkville Endoscopy's website says it is an "ambulatory surgical center" that has been "approved by the Department of Health." The description of its accreditations is blank.

"Yorkville Endoscopy is a state of the art facility, staffed by highly experienced endoscopists whose mission is to provide safe and compassionate care to patients and their families," the website says.

More from CNN at http://www.cnn.com/

title: Joan Rivers Dick Cavett 1985
Talk Show Hosts Collection on Letterman, Part 4 of 7: Joan Rivers
description:
This is my own supplementary material to the six-part documentary "The Story of Late Night" that will air on CNN. I selected seven talk-show hosts who had guested on Dave. Fourth up: Joan Rivers.

Late Night:
1. May 13, 1986. Surprise walk-on after canceling as scheduled guest. Soon after she announced her upcoming talk show without Johnny Carson's knowledge. Her show debuts October 9.
2. October 9, 1986. Guest Martin Mull mentions Joan's talk-show premiere.

Late Show:
3. July 30, 2002. "QVC."
4. January 17, 2003. Hosts E!'s coverage of the Golden Globes Awards.
5. August 1, 2003. Cape Thing.
6. July 22, 2010. Documentary: "Joan Rivers, A Piece of Work." Clip deleted due to copyright caution.
7. January 14, 2011. "Joan and Melissa: Joan Knows Best."
8. May 13, 2011. "Fashion Police" on E!
9. February 16, 2012. "Joan and Melissa: Joan Knows Best."
10. June 4, 2012. Book: _I Hate Everyone â€¦ Starting with Me,_
11. February 26, 2013. "Joan and Melissa: Joan Knows Best."
12. July 8, 2014. Book: _Diary of a Mad Diva._ 

13. Dave's eulogy: September 4, 2014.

From WikiPedia:
The Joan Rivers Show is an American talk show hosted by comedian Joan Rivers that premiered on September 5, 1989 in broadcast syndication. The show aired for four seasons and ended in 1993. The show was nominated for numerous Emmy Awards, with Rivers winning the Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Talk Show Host in 1990. The series was produced by PGHM Productions, Joan Rivers's production company, and distributed by Tribune Entertainment.

In the mid-1990's the show was repeated on the E! TV network for several months. In early 2019 the show began re-airing on the Decades TV network, and it became available on the Roku streaming device.
Rivers had previously hosted late-night talk show entitled The Late Show with Joan Rivers which got canceled in May 1987.

Bloomberg Television's "Taking Stock With Pimm Fox" brings you cutting edge market analysis after the closing bell. Anchor Pimm Fox, together with a team Bloomberg's leading on-air reporters such as Carol Massar, Cristina Alesci, and Julie Hyman provide more than just the earnings headlines. On "Taking Stock," you'll learn the reasons driving earnings per share, revenues, net income, quarterly outlooks, dividend payments and share buybacks from the companies leading the S&P 500, the Nasdaq, and the Dow Jones Industrial Average. Top companies often covered on "Taking Stock" include Best Buy, Carnival, Yahoo, Goldman Sachs, JPMorgan, Apple, Clearwire, Netflix, Google, Amazon, General Electric, Chesapeake Energy. Additionally, "Taking Stock" features interviews with cultural figures and a weekly "Mystery Guest" segment. Broadcasting daily from Bloomberg's headquarters in New York at 5pm ET/2 pm PT, "Taking Stock" is the place to get not just breaking business news - but the context of what it means going forward.

title: Joy Behar on The Joan Rivers Show (9/26/89)
description:
Joan's guest is comedienne Joy Behar. Joy discusses her past jobs, including working at Good Morning America and being fired for being hostile and organizing "lesbian hour" with her coworkers. She also talks about her divorce and becoming a stand-up comedian. Behar expresses her love for being single and her dislike for marriage. The conversation also covers topics such as plastic surgery, working out, and beach-going. The segment ends with a discussion about Barbara Bush and George Bush's marriage.

Aired September 26, 1989.

The Joan Rivers Show premiered on September 5th, 1989 hosted by comedienne Joan Rivers. This syndicated series from PGHM Productions Inc for Tribune Entertainment was produced by Steve Ober. Celebrity guests and interesting and controversial topics were the subject of each hour long program. Joan's entertaining personality along with her acerbic and brash outbursts garnered her an EMMY for Outstanding host of a talk show in 1990. Airing daily in the mornings or early afternoons in some areas.

Aired Daily 11:00 AM on FOX.

title: Bette Davis' daughter B.D. Hyman on The Joan Rivers Show (1991)
description: In September 1991, B.D. Hyman, appeared 'The Joan Rivers Show', during which she repeated her familiar litany of horror stories about her mother, film icon Bette Davis. This time, however, there was a twist: Bette's fifteen-year-old grandson, Justin, who was six when he last saw her, came on the show and offered support for his mother's stories. He told his own harrowing tale of being threatned by Bette with a fireplace poker (An event that was not mentioned in either of B.D.'s books.)

title: Fran Drescher on The Joan Rivers Show (5/25/90)
description:
Joan's guest is actress Fran Drescher. Fran talks about bringing her dog, Chester, to a screen test for a new movie with Robin Williams. Chester got the part, and so did Fran. Fran explains that Chester was chosen because he is obnoxious, which was in the script, and he growled and barked at Robin during the screen test, making it more interesting and funny. Fran also talks about her experience with Robin Williams in a fake motel room where they filmed a scene for the movie. They were both scantly clothed, and Robin had a lot of body hair, which Fran found amusing. Fran also discusses her accent and how it has helped her become specific about her comedic roles.

Aired May 25, 1990.

The Joan Rivers Show premiered on September 5th, 1989 hosted by comedienne Joan Rivers. This syndicated series from PGHM Productions Inc for Tribune Entertainment was produced by Steve Ober. Celebrity guests and interesting and controversial topics were the subject of each hour long program. Joan's entertaining personality along with her acerbic and brash outbursts garnered her an EMMY for Outstanding host of a talk show in 1990. Airing daily in the mornings or early afternoons in some areas.

Aired Daily 11:00 AM on FOX.

title: The Joan Rivers Show: The Dark Side of Adoption Part 2 of 2
description: In 1990 Joan Rivers had a short-lied morning talk show. ** to correct Dunne:
Dr. Oziel did not tape the October 31, 1989 confession. Oziel later recorded his notes about the session. The only recording made by Oziel which had Lyle and Erik Menendez' voices on it was recorded on December 11, 1989 and it was recorded with the brothers' knowledge.
Judalon Smyth was eavesdropping on October 31st when Erik Menendez confessed. Smyth only went to the police in March 1990, to file charges against Oziel. Smyth also told police she knew the brothers killed their parents. **

Karen Lamm was an actress and aspiring producer when she met Kitty Menendez in 1988 at a business party held at the Menendez home. In 1990, CBS announced they were working on a project about the Menendez murders. Karen Lamm contacted them and provided information. Lamm was paid and credited as executive producer in the television film Menendez: A Killing in Beverly Hills.

The group found their greatest success in the United States, with five Top 40 hits in the US, all charting between 1983 and 1987, including "Dance Hall Days" (No. 16 in the summer of 1984), "Everybody Have Fun Tonight" (No. 2 in 1986) and "Let's Go!" (No. 9 in 1987).

title: 2. Your Song (Elton John - The Joan Rivers Show: 10/9/1986)
description:
Hello you crazy subscribers! After getting beat up by my co-host over the last few weeks (see the recent review on â€œSongs From The West Coastâ€ for the reasons why), I have recovered enough to begin uploading shows again! This is a â€œquick uploadâ€ for the channel and the subject matter concerns Eltonâ€™s performances on the Joan Rivers Show from October 1986. There are three sources used on this upload with varying quality (each song has its own source), but itâ€™s a good listen overall and definitely worth checking out!

By October 1986, Eltonâ€™s vocal troubles were very apparent and affected just about every facet of his voice. His tone was scratchy, his range was severely clipped, and his famous falsetto was almost completely extinguished. Despite the vocal damage, Elton still pushed through the last handful of dates on the North American tour and continued his vocal destruction through the state of California (there are recordings from Oakland, Costa Mesa, and two Los Angeles shows showcasing this - with the worst results being at Los Angeles). During this run of shows, Elton went onto the Joan Rivers show to promote his new album at the time (â€œLeather Jacketsâ€) and performed three songs for everybody. Nowâ€¦ time to talk about them!

â€œThe Bitch Is Backâ€ has the distinct honor of being the only live version (outside of the â€œTop Of The Popsâ€ version from 1974) that was played in the original key of Ab. Despite the excellent house band and the great energy overall, Eltonâ€™s voice is in tatters and sounds incredibly rough throughout the performance. He sounds scratchy and strained on nearly every higher note, and he nearly train-wrecks after the first chorus (he comes in too early with the second verseâ€™s lyrics). Adding to the mayhem is the fact that Joan Rivers and Cher add their voices to the song and frequently sing out of tune on top of everything. Definitely not one of the best versions overall! â€œYour Songâ€ sounds incredibly rough vocally (especially as the song progresses), but Elton has some moments where his old voice breaks through the roughness and is able to phrase parts of the song nicely. He also tries to oversing the song like he would usually do during this era, but his rough voice makes the note choices sound extremely grating overall. Finally, there is a snippet of â€œTwist And Shoutâ€ that sounds energetic and I wished that the performance was complete!

ENJOY!!!

title: The Joan Rivers Show | Bumper | 1991 | WAAY 31 Huntsville Alabama
description:
The Joan Rivers Show | Bumper | 1991 | WAAY 31 Huntsville Alabama

The Joan Rivers Show is an American talk show hosted by comedian Joan Rivers that premiered on September 5, 1989 in broadcast syndication. The show aired for five seasons and ended on December 31, 1993.[1][2] The show was nominated for numerous Emmy Awards, with Rivers winning the Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Talk Show Host in 1990.[3][4] The series was produced by PGHM Productions, Joan Rivers's production company, and distributed by Tribune Entertainment.
Rivers had previously hosted late-night talk show entitled The Late Show with Joan Rivers which got canceled in May 1987.[

title: 1991 I Love Lucy 40th Anniversary Reunion | The Joan Rivers Show | Desi Arnaz Jr, Keith Thibodeaux
description:
Most of the October 14th, 1991 episode of The Joan Rivers Show feauring a 40th anniversary cast & crew reunion of I Love Lucy. Guest include Desi Arnaz Jr, Keith Thibodeaux (Little Ricky), writers Bob Schiller and Bob Weiskopf, hair stylist Irma Kusely, and Lucy author Bart Andrews.

From my personal VHS collection recorded via Armstrong Cable in Medina, Ohio.

I Love Lucy is an American television sitcom that originally aired on CBS from October 15, 1951, to May 6, 1957, with a total of 180 half-hour episodes spanning six seasons. The series starred Lucille Ball and her husband Desi Arnaz, along with Vivian Vance and William Frawley, and follows the life of Lucy Ricardo (Ball), a young, middle-class housewife living in New York City, who often concocts plans with her best friends and landlords, Ethel and Fred Mertz (Vance and Frawley), to appear alongside her bandleader husband, Ricky Ricardo (Arnaz), in his nightclub. Lucy is depicted trying numerous schemes to mingle with and be a part of show business. After the series ended in 1957, a modified version of the show continued for three more seasons, with 13 one-hour specials, which ran from 1957 to 1960. It was first known as The Lucille Ballâ€“Desi Arnaz Show, and later, in reruns, as The Lucyâ€“Desi Comedy Hour.

title: SWEET DREW BARRYMORE (ALMOST 12 YRS OLD) ON JOAN RIVERS SHOW, LATE 1986 OR EARLY 1987 (472
EL VEZ on the JOAN RIVERS SHOW
description: 1991, spring tour of the book I AM ELVIS. I was made the leader of the misfit Elviâ€™ & we did a tour of Book Stores, Restaurants & TV shows to promo. It was great fun. They realized I had that â€œX factorâ€ & let me be the head for these events. It was great to be on the Joan Rivers Show. I am amused by the 90â€™s living room sets. Also on that show was the late great Dizzy Gillespie. I was the only one in our group who knew who he was?! I got to chat w/him & watch him warm up in the green room. His cheeks were amazingly elastic & blew up like giant puffer fish. The maroon jumpsuit was made of crushed velvet. I would say â€œI crushed it myself!â€ I was modeling it after the Mexican Huehue Dancers meet Elvis. It had a sequined Virgin de Guadalupe on the capes back. I donated it to the GRACELAND TOO Museum in Holly Springs MS. But I think it was lost in the fire after the shooting.

Dream Stalkers Gone Wild: 1989 College Boy Edition (Joan Rivers Show)
description:
Love is a powerful drug!

Colorful married couple William Hunter and his wife, Cheryl, ride out the storm in this 1990 episode of "The Joan Rivers Show" on location in Hollywood. 

William made news for his 2 1/2-day hunger strike aimed at getting Cheryl, an aspiring singer, a shot on late night's "The Arsenio Hall Show". Hunter had camped out in front of Hall's studio, insisting he wouldn't leave until he got to meet the host and secure a spot on his show for Cheryl to showcase her vocal talents. 

As incredible as William's dedication to Cheryl isâ€”as demonstrated through his months-long hunger strike and days-long studio camp outâ€”it's all the more remarkable knowing he rode a bicycle from Birmingham to Los Angeles to find national TV cameras, nearly getting half-naked for Joan Rivers in the process.

William left Birmingham on his bike odyssey on October 27, 1989.

And while Cheryl monitored William's publicity stunt safe at home in Birmingham, in another corner of the South, college freshmen were starting their adult life.

Kenneth Williams on the Joan Rivers show in 1986
description:
Kenneth Williams on the Joan Rivers show in 1986 - incredibly funny!

Joan asks a few questions and Kenneth goes from one character to the next.

Joan Rivers was an American comedian, actress, and television personality.

Kenneth Williams was born on February 22, 1926, in Islington, London, England. He began his acting career in repertory theatre and gained early recognition for his comedic talent. Known for his quick wit, flamboyant mannerisms, and distinctive vocal delivery, Williams developed a loyal fan base for his comedic performances. He often delivered clever one-liners and had a knack for improvisation.
